A jury recommended life without parole for a man found guilty of causing a train crash that killed 11 in Los Angeles.
The defendant, Juan Alvarez, apologized for his actions, claiming he never intended to harm others.
Prosecutors allege he staged the crash for attention from his wife.
Alvarez's troubled past, including abuse and drug addiction, was highlighted in court.
Despite his remorse, prosecutors seek the death penalty.
Witnesses testified to Alvarez's difficult upbringing, shedding light on his mental state.
The jury deliberates between life in prison or execution for Alvarez, as his family pleads for mercy.
